					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8021480#post-4146961</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8021480/scp-4455#post-4146961</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Sat, 09 Feb 2019 03:39:32 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>DarkStuff</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1581620</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Well, you can’t please everyone, heheh. I posted a shorter version of this before, for these precise reasons, but it wasn’t received well. This is the rewrite, which is faring <em>much</em> better, so my hand is forced, as it were, to keep it as is.</p> <p>Also, not documenting would surely mean we would have nothing to read. But, however&#8230; maybe they realised this loophole for the <em>second</em> time they contained him, but it’s not written here, for that reason &gt;:3</p> <p>EDIT: <em>I might also point out that it has the</em> ability <em>to shorten narratives. It's not a necessary action for it to take. You could theoretically have a very long narrative about Streamliner, as long as he didn't use his power on your story.</em></p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8021480#post-4146637</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8021480/scp-4455#post-4146637</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Fri, 08 Feb 2019 20:07:02 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>psul</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>2156983</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Yes, this is intended to be silly, but that doesn’t require the lack of internal consistency displayed here. The premise asks that we accept that real life, as it happens, is a “narrative” on which this anomaly can operate. Even if one goes along with the idea that this is a universe where that concept doesn’t even warrant a mention in the report (and that’s a little far from reality for my taste), the Foundation here still fails to take two obvious actions:</p> <p>1) Don’t document the capture or containment of the anomaly - there is then no narrative to abridge.</p> <p>2) Point out to the anomaly that a record of 29 containment attempts and then breach reports is itself a lengthy narrative, as the Foundation won’t stop trying. If the anomaly’s goal is summarisation, it might be a shorter story if it immediately submitted to capture and stayed there. The end.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
